\begin{IDEA}
**Title: Symmetry-Driven Thermodynamic Optimization of CO₂ Sorbents via Isostructural Substitution**

**Description:** This study identifies high-performance CO₂ capture candidates by mapping the carbonation energy landscape across stable, isostructural oxide-carbonate pairs. By grouping materials by `space_group` and `crystal_system`, we isolate the influence of crystallographic symmetry on the thermodynamic favorability of the reaction $\Delta E = E(M_xCO_3) - E(M_xO_y) - E(CO_2)$. The model will prioritize pairs sharing identical symmetry operators to mitigate structural noise and DFT error, focusing on candidates where the oxide precursor resides on the convex hull (`is_stable = True`). We will evaluate whether specific space groups, such as $P2_1/c$ or $R\bar{3}c$, act as structural descriptors that consistently lower the thermodynamic barrier to carbonation across diverse metal cations (Li, Mg, Ca, Fe). This approach bypasses the need for explicit polymorph-pairing by leveraging the dataset’s structural diversity to identify symmetry-constrained materials that optimize CO₂ uptake efficiency.
\end{IDEA}


